<span class="displaytext"><b>at roundtables and town halls in hanover, keene, and nashua, granite staters discuss the consequences of our broken politics</b><p>manchester, nh -- at a roundtable at jesse's restaurant in hanover this morning, senator (candidate full) kicked off a day of discussion with new hampshire voters about the need for real change in washington. (candidate last) sat down for breakfast with a small group to discuss the way that broken culture in washington affects the lives of everyday americans. later in the day (candidate last) was to meet with voters at a roundtable at lindy's diner in keene. </p><p>"we've got a politics in washington that isn't working for the people anymore, and we're going to have to build a movement to overcome the status quo," senator (candidate last) said. </p><p>in manchester earlier this summer, (candidate last) unveiled what would be the most sweeping ethics reform package in history and pledged to sign it on his first day as president. </p><p>"americans of every background and belief are hungry for a new kind of politics--a people's politics that reconnects them with their government; one that offers not just a vote at the ballot box, but a voice in washington and an assurance that the leaders we send there will hear it," senator (candidate last) said in that speech. "the people i've met across this country don't just want reform for reform's sake, they want reform that will help pay their doctor's bills, or ensure that their tax dollars are spent wisely, or put us on the path to energy independence. they want real reform and they're tired of the lobbyists standing in the way." </p><p>(candidate last) has championed ethics reform for his entire career, passing the first major ethics reform bill in decades as a member of the illinois senate and serving as the (PARTY NAME)' point person on ethics in the u.s. senate. this month the senate passed an ethics package based largely on legislation introduced by (candidate last) and senator russ feingold requiring disclosure of "bundling" activity, restrictions on the use of corporate jets, and a ban on gifts from lobbyists. </p><p>in addition to the hanover and keene roundtables, (candidate last) was to hold a rally in keene and town hall on changing washington in nashua.</p></span>



